# Theme Implementation Guidelines

## Theme Architecture
- Use a single source of truth for theme management
- Implement theme at the root level only
- Use data attributes instead of classes for theme switching
- Keep theme state in a dedicated context provider

## Theme Provider Structure
```typescript
// Correct implementation
"use client"

import { createContext, useContext, useEffect, useState } from "react"

type Theme = "light" | "dark"

const ThemeProviderContext = createContext<{
  theme: Theme
  setTheme: (theme: Theme) => void
}>({
  theme: "light",
  setTheme: () => null,
})

export function ThemeProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false)
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState<Theme>("light")

  useEffect(() => {
    setMounted(true)
    const storedTheme = localStorage.getItem("theme") as Theme
    if (storedTheme) setTheme(storedTheme)
  }, [])

  useEffect(() => {
    if (!mounted) return
    document.body.setAttribute("data-theme", theme)
    localStorage.setItem("theme", theme)
  }, [theme, mounted])

  return (
    <ThemeProviderContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </ThemeProviderContext.Provider>
  )
}
```

## CSS Implementation
```css
/* Correct implementation */
@layer base {
  :root {
    --background: 150 30% 98%;
    --foreground: 150 10% 20%;
    /* other light theme variables */
  }

  [data-theme="dark"] {
    --background: 150 10% 95%;
    --foreground: 150 10% 20%;
    /* other dark theme variables */
  }
}
```

## DO NOT
- ❌ Add theme classes to HTML elements
- ❌ Implement multiple theme providers
- ❌ Force theme changes in components
- ❌ Use theme classes for styling
- ❌ Mix theme implementation approaches

## DO
- ✅ Use data-theme attribute for theme switching
- ✅ Keep theme state in a single context
- ✅ Implement theme at the root level only
- ✅ Use CSS variables for theme values
- ✅ Handle theme changes in the provider only

## Theme Usage in Components
```typescript
// Correct usage
"use client"

import { useTheme } from "@/components/theme-provider"

export function ThemeToggle() {
  const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme()
  
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setTheme(theme === "light" ? "dark" : "light")}>
      Toggle Theme
    </button>
  )
}
```

## Error Prevention
1. Always check for mounted state before accessing window/document
2. Use proper TypeScript types for theme values
3. Implement proper error boundaries
4. Handle theme persistence safely
5. Test theme switching in different scenarios

## Testing Requirements
- Test theme persistence across page reloads
- Verify theme changes don't cause layout shifts
- Ensure theme works with SSR
- Test theme with different components
- Verify theme state consistency

## Performance Considerations
- Minimize theme-related re-renders
- Use CSS variables for theme values
- Implement proper memoization
- Avoid unnecessary theme state updates
- Optimize theme-related CSS

## Accessibility
- Ensure proper color contrast in both themes
- Test theme with screen readers
- Maintain consistent focus states
- Keep text readable in all themes
- Support system theme preferences

## Maintenance
- Document theme-related changes
- Keep theme implementation simple
- Follow consistent naming conventions
- Update theme documentation
- Review theme implementation regularly 